<div id="review_2548630636" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2548630636" />
    <a title="Barb in Maryland" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1166624-barb-in-maryland"><img alt="Barb in Maryland" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1211208170p2/1166624.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2548630636?book_show_action=true">Oct 03, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Barb in Maryland" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Barb in Maryland" href="/user/show/1166624-barb-in-maryland">Barb in Maryland</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1166624-barb-in-maryland?shelf=mystery-thriller-goodies">mystery-thriller-goodies</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1166624-barb-in-maryland?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2548630636" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2093350091700451906">September 1140 finds a new novice being admitted to the Abbey. Young Meriet Apsley is insistent that it is his choice to join the Benedictine brothers; that he is not being forced by his stern, cold father. However, Cadfael and others have their doubts. When Meriet starts having loud nightmares many are disturbed and frightened; Cadfael is curious and suspects a trauma of some sort in the young man&apos;s past.<br/>In October, there came an important visitor. Canon Eluard, returning to Winchester from a s</span>
  <span id="freeText2093350091700451906" style="display:none">September 1140 finds a new novice being admitted to the Abbey. Young Meriet Apsley is insistent that it is his choice to join the Benedictine brothers; that he is not being forced by his stern, cold father. However, Cadfael and others have their doubts. When Meriet starts having loud nightmares many are disturbed and frightened; Cadfael is curious and suspects a trauma of some sort in the young man's past.<br />In October, there came an important visitor. Canon Eluard, returning to Winchester from a successful diplomatic mission to the Earl of Chester, is seeking a missing clerk to the Bishop of Winchester. Peter Clemence was tasked with delivering a message to the Earl but never made it. He was last seen in early September at the home of a distant kinsman, Leoric Apsley, young Meriet's father.<br />As autumn progresses to winter, Cadfael and sheriff Hugh Beringar work a double investigation--find the missing clerk, find out what Meriet is hiding. When Clemence's body is finally found, both investigations become more complicated, with even more unanswered questions.<br />This is a very twisty set of mysteries, where the remote political situation is as important as the personal. Meriet is a very troubled young man, but could he also be a murderer? Cadfael certainly doesn't believe he is. Unfortunately for Hugh, no one seems to have any reason to murder the clerk.<br />At last, a vital clue is discovered and a trap is set for the killer. There's a rousing climax, with a startling development that took me by surprise. The final resolution is satisfying with (almost) everyone getting their just deserts. <br />It was nice to see Brother Mark again and to spend a bit of time with the lepers at St Giles. Cadfael is never just a sleuth, but also excels at dispensing sage advice and being very wise to the foibles of his fellow humans. I always feel so comforted (as well as entertained) when I read these books.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2093350091700451906" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


