<div id="review_4125978704" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4125978704" />
    <a title="Carlos Mock" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25246406-carlos-mock"><img alt="Carlos Mock" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1503856648p2/25246406.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4125978704?book_show_action=true">Jul 20, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carlos Mock" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carlos Mock" href="/user/show/25246406-carlos-mock">Carlos Mock</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4125978704" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8553593581342136800">The Devil&apos;s Novice (Chronicles of Brother Cadfael, #8) by Ellis Peters<br/><br/>Although this is the eighth book in the series, this is a stand-alone book and you don&apos;t need to read any of the prior books to enjoy it.<br/><br/>In September of 1140, at the Abbey of Saint Peter and Saint Paul in Shrewsbury, Meriet Aspley is brought in by his father, Lord Aspley to enter the novitiate at the Abby. Soon it becomes clear that Meriet is troubled. He starts having nightmares and yells &quot;Barbary.&quot; The other novices think he</span>
  <span id="freeText8553593581342136800" style="display:none">The Devil's Novice (Chronicles of Brother Cadfael, #8) by Ellis Peters<br /><br />Although this is the eighth book in the series, this is a stand-alone book and you don't need to read any of the prior books to enjoy it.<br /><br />In September of 1140, at the Abbey of Saint Peter and Saint Paul in Shrewsbury, Meriet Aspley is brought in by his father, Lord Aspley to enter the novitiate at the Abby. Soon it becomes clear that Meriet is troubled. He starts having nightmares and yells "Barbary." The other novices think he's possessed by the devil.<br /><br />Master Peter Clemence has gone missing after a visit to his cousin, Lord Aspley. Soon Clements horse is found and a low-class beggar, Harald is found with Clemens dagger and accused of his murder.<br /><br />Brother Cadfaell, the hero of the series, concludes that Harald is innocent, since a poor person would not have walked away from the scene and left all the valuable possessions. When Meriet learns that Harald is being accused, he suddenly confesses to the murder. But Brother Cadfael knows Meriet is lying and sets out a plan to uncover the real killer - and in the process uncovers treason against King Stephen, who is fighting for the throne of England against Empress Maud, his half-sister.<br /><br />Narrated from the third-person point of view, this is a very sweet tale of "who done it," and a nice read set in the backdrop of medieval England. <br /><br />Recommended!</span>
  <a data-text-id="8553593581342136800" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


