    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1898474381" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1898474381" />
    <a title="Lance" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46538050-lance"><img alt="Lance" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1441159873p2/46538050.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1898474381?book_show_action=true">Feb 06, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lance" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lance" href="/user/show/46538050-lance">Lance</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=2017">2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=series">series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=looking-for-clues">looking-for-clues</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1898474381" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15014612758890996867">&quot;<i>Those who have been blinded by too great a light do not see, cannot afford to see, the pain they cause.</i>&quot;<br/><br/>Oooh.<br/><br/>&quot;<i>Some who thus take fire burn to the day of their death, and leave a trail of radiance for generations to come. Other fires sink for want of fuel. Time would discover what young Meriet&apos;s small, desperate flame portended.</i>&quot;<br/><br/><i>The Devil&apos;s Novice</i> is more of a psychological thriller than a murder mystery. It centres around a young, truculent new member of the monastery who demands to take the mo</span>
  <span id="freeText15014612758890996867" style="display:none">"<i>Those who have been blinded by too great a light do not see, cannot afford to see, the pain they cause.</i>"<br /><br />Oooh.<br /><br />"<i>Some who thus take fire burn to the day of their death, and leave a trail of radiance for generations to come. Other fires sink for want of fuel. Time would discover what young Meriet's small, desperate flame portended.</i>"<br /><br /><i>The Devil's Novice</i> is more of a psychological thriller than a murder mystery. It centres around a young, truculent new member of the monastery who demands to take the monks' vows as soon as possible despite giving himself over at 19 from a rich inheritance. Suspicious? Even more so when he begins to be wracked by nightmares with all the characteristics of demonic possession. "<i>There were words in it, but no distinguishable word, it gabbled and stormed like a malediction, broken by sobbing pauses to draw in breath.</i>" A scary prospect for an isolated young novice.<br />But Brother Cadfael isn't fooled for one second. "<i>'It is his tameness that concerns me, for by nature he is wild.'</i>" Cadfael doesn't buy into all this nonsense about devils, and when it comes to light that an important diplomat stayed at the young man's house the week before he joined the monastery, Cadfael strives to unwrap this mental trauma. He is characteristically shrewd with words and ruthlessly logical. "<i>'Give me the lad's answers in his very words. Where there's nothing of interest to be found in the content, it's worth taking a close look at the manner.'</i>"<br />Luckily, he has his faithful allies Brother Mark and Hugh Beringer, both of whom are on top form in this instalment. Hugh is droll (best quote: "<i>'The search for Peter Clemence has become, to all intents and purposes, a search for his horse.'</i>"), harsh but exceedingly fair, and really has some sexy authority about him in this book. And sweet Mark is the spiritual saviour of Meriet the tormented novice. "<i>Brother Mark prayer, not be words, but by igniting a candle-flame within himself, which burned incredibly tall, and sent up entreaty to Meriet. It was all for him.</i>" It was a lovely ending that Mark was sponsored by Meriet's family to complete his priest training. Only one more step to sainthood!<br />The setting and history of this novel was the most interesting yet in the series. King Stephen is desperate to butter up the petty kings of northern England, who, unhappy with earldoms and castles, are plotting a betrayal of gross greed. This viciousness trickles down even into the petty noblemen of the Welsh border. The revelation of this treatury is equally scandalous! "<i>Against the heavy blue of Roswitha's cloak, the great broach, aggressively male, stood out brilliantly.</i>" Treatury! Sorcery! What more could you want?<br /><br />"<i>'Whatever devil is possessing young Meriet is plaguing me by contagion, and I want it exorcised at all costs!'</i>"</span>
  <a data-text-id="15014612758890996867" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

